the pitch deck is below.    Convert this into a site for directorforgood.org. Get rid of all the unnecessary images because this is a new company. And a new site. 



1. Cover



Director

 The AI-native operating system and forward-deployed backbone for nonprofits

Turning under-resourced founders into fundable, operationally tight organizations

directorforgood.org

[Your Name], Founder & CEO

2. Problem – Founders Are the Whole Leadership Team

Nonprofit founders are carrying 5 jobs on 1 salary.

They’re expected to:

Lead programs and vision

Raise money (major gifts, grants, events)

Run operations and finance

Own communications and storytelling

Manage staff, boards, and compliance

When funding tightens and staff are cut, all of this collapses back onto one person.

 Promising orgs plateau at $300–600k or quietly shut down — not for lack of impact, but for lack of backbone.

3. Problem – Downshifted Orgs (Beachhead)

Our initial focus: orgs that already proved they can raise $400k–$1M.

These orgs:

Have real donor and community relationships

Have a history of 7-figure budgets or close

But in the current funding environment:

They’ve laid off staff

The founder is back to doing everything

Many are considering shutting down despite strong demand for their work

This hits founders of color especially hard, as equity-era funding retrenches and flexible money disappears.

These leaders don’t need another tool. They need a backbone.

4. Broken Options

Existing solutions don’t fit this stage.

DIY SaaS stack

CRMs, grant tools, accounting, email…

Founders don’t have time (or staff) to integrate and maintain them.

Consultants & agencies

Project-based, expensive, and seen as “overhead.”

Advice without ongoing operational responsibility.

Rebuilding staff

Bay Area-ish:

ED: $100–150k

Ops/Finance: ~100k

Development: ~100k

Comms/Program ops: 60–100k

$360–450k/year just for the backbone on a fragile budget.

There is no integrated, AI-native backbone designed for $400k–$1M orgs that have real relationships but no team.

5. Director – What We Are

Director is an AI-native backbone and forward-deployed team for nonprofits.

We provide:

Director OS – a vertical operating system for:

Revenue & relationships

Runway & finance

Ops & compliance

Board & funder narratives

A Director Pod – shared leadership capacity:

Forward-Deployed Director (FDD)

Finance/ops leadership

Later: dedicated development & ops roles as we scale

We plug into an existing org and donor base and give them the leadership bench they can’t afford to rebuild alone.

6. Fundraising Philosophy – Relationships First

Director is built around major gifts and real relationships, not grant roulette.

Durable funding comes from:

Major donors

Anchor institutions

Long-term partners

Grants are part of the picture, but:

They are downstream of relationships

“Open call” grant-chasing is mostly a distraction for this segment

Director’s focus:

Map and grow the major gifts pipeline

Prepare founders for high-stakes meetings

Use grants strategically once relationships exist

Director is a relationship and revenue engine, not a shot-in-the-dark grant factory.

7. The Director Pod – Capacity Ramp (Lean First, Then Scale)

Pods scale from 4 → 8 → 16 orgs as the OS and agents mature.

Year 1 – Lean “Proto-Pod”

Team:

You (Founder/CEO)

1 Forward-Deployed Director (FDD)

1 Finance Director (covering finance + ops)

1 Founding Engineer

Capacity:

FDD deeply embedded with up to 4 orgs

Finance Director builds cross-org finance/ops playbooks and workflows

Engineer builds Director OS + first agents alongside you

Phase 2 – 8 orgs

Mature core agents take on most repetitive finance/ops/reporting tasks

Same FDD + Finance Director structure supports more orgs, with additional FDD capacity added as needed

Phase 3 – 16 orgs

2+ FDDs each focused on 4–6 orgs

Finance/ops/development leadership scaled across all 16 using agents and standardized playbooks

Agents perform the recurring work; Pods focus on relationships and decisions.

8. Director OS – Product Overview

One pane of glass for an org’s backbone.

Director OS brings together:

Revenue & Relationships

Major gifts map and warm funder pipeline

Next-best actions for key relationships

Runway & Finance

Live cash forecasts and scenarios

Budget vs. actuals visibility

Ops & Compliance

Recurring task engine (payroll, filings, renewals)

Checklists and playbooks

Narratives & Reporting

Board decks and updates

Funder reports and impact one-pagers

Data flows in from email, calendar, finance systems, docs, and existing CRMs so the OS reflects reality, not just what someone remembered to log.

9. AI Agents – How We 2–4x Human Capacity

Specialized agents do the repetitive work; humans do the judgment.

Examples:

Major Gifts Agent

Scans email, calendar, CRM for each org

Maintains relationship maps

Suggests outreach and drafts donor emails and meeting briefs

Finance & Runway Agent

Pulls accounting and bank data

Proposes categorizations, reconciliations, cash-flow updates

Raises alerts on anomalies and runway risks

Ops & Compliance Agent

Runs recurring checklists (payroll, filings, renewals)

Generates drafts, reminders, and task lists

Board & Reporting Agent

Assembles board decks and funder reports from live data

Keeps a “board-ready” view up to date

Pattern:

Agents explore, compile, and draft.

 FDDs and Directors review, edit, and decide.

This is the same shift we’re seeing in engineering (Cursor/Devin-style agents) and customer ops — we’re applying it to nonprofit backbones.

10. Economics – Why This Makes Sense

Director makes a serious backbone affordable and scalable.

Illustrative comparison for a ~$500–700k org:

Rebuilding the traditional backbone:

ED: $100–150k

Ops/Finance: ~100k

Dev: ~100k

Comms/Program ops: 60–100k

Total backbone: $360–450k/year

With Director:

ED/founder: $100–150k

Director Pod (Year 1 pricing for early orgs): target ~$80–120k/year

Total backbone: $180–270k/year

As Pods scale from 4 → 8 → 16 orgs and agents automate more of the workflows:

Pod-level gross margins expand

Per-org economics improve while keeping human leadership involvement high

11. Why Now – AI Agents + Nonprofit Pressure

Two timing curves are intersecting.

Agentic AI is production-ready.

“AI coworkers” are already shipping in engineering, finance, and customer operations.

A small human team can now manage far more complexity with agents doing most of the clicking.

Nonprofits are under structural pressure.

Orgs that once had $1M+ budgets are losing staff and struggling to maintain operations and reporting.

Funders are more selective and want grantees with credible backbones and visibility.

Director sits at this intersection:

 an AI-native backbone delivered by a lean, forward-deployed team to orgs that cannot justify rebuilding full in-house leadership.

12. Go-to-Market

We start where we already have pull.

Existing relationships

First 2–4 orgs from founders and orgs you’re already effectively “directing.”

Downshifted $1M orgs

Target leaders who have proved they can raise $400k–$1M but had to cut backbone staff.

Funder collaborations

Position Director as a capacity-building line item that makes grantees more investable and easier to monitor.

Sales motion:

Short diagnostic: map “today vs with Director” team and budget.

Demo Director OS + agents and show what gets taken off the founder’s plate.

Close annual retainers, expand the number of orgs and scope over time.

13. Business Model & QSBS-Friendly Structure

AI-native vertical SaaS with embedded forward-deployed team.

Revenue model

Annual retainers per org, tied to budget band and complexity

Long-term goal: multiple Pods, each supporting up to 16 orgs on the OS

Cost structure

Lean Pods (FDD + Finance Director) supported by agents and product

Founder & Engineer drive product/agent development that compounds across all clients

QSBS-aware design

U.S. C-corp, building an active, product-centric operating business

Assets are primarily software, data models, and operating infrastructure

Company is structured so founders and early investors can potentially access QSBS benefits (subject to their own tax advice)

14. Team – Lean Year-1 Plan

Small, high-leverage founding team with 12 months of runway.

Founder & CEO (you)

Product vision, sales, fundraising, relationships

Acts as early FDD alongside hire as needed

Forward-Deployed Director (hire #1)

Deep nonprofit ops + fundraising

Embedded across the first ~4 orgs

Finance Director (hire #2)

Covers finance + ops across the initial pod

Designs playbooks the agents will run

Founding Engineer (hire #3)

Builds Director OS and the first wave of agents with you

Target raise for ~12 months runway (illustrative):

Lean team + non-people costs → roughly $800k–$1M

Early org retainers reduce net burn as you ramp to 4 paying customers.

15. Roadmap & Ask

Roadmap

0–12 months (this raise):

Hire FDD, Finance Director, Founding Engineer

Onboard 2–4 orgs

Ship v1 Director OS and core agents (finance, ops, reporting, major gifts support)

Prove: 4-org pod with agents delivers clear revenue and stability lift

12–24 months:

Scale pod to 8 orgs

Harden agents and playbooks

Add additional FDD/finance/ops capacity as revenues justify

24+ months:

16-org pods on mature OS

Multiple pods focused on key verticals (arts, youth, community, etc.)

Ask

Raise $800k–$1.0M to:

Fund 12+ months of lean team and product development

Prove the 4 → 8 → 16 org capacity story with real customers

Build Director into the AI-native backbone for the orgs that can least afford to lose theirs.

+ import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
+ import { renderToBuffer } from '@react-pdf/renderer';
+ import { DirectorPitchDeck } from '@/lib/pdf/deck-pdf';
+ 
+ export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic';
+ 
+ export async function GET() {
+   try {
+     // Generate PDF buffer
+     const pdfBuffer = await renderToBuffer(DirectorPitchDeck());
+     
+     // Return as downloadable PDF
+     return new NextResponse(pdfBuffer, {
+       status: 200,
+       headers: {
+         'Content-Type': 'application/pdf',
+         'Content-Disposition': 'attachment; filename="Director-Pitch-Deck.pdf"',
+         'Content-Length': pdfBuffer.length.toString(),
+       },
+     });
+   } catch (error) {
+     console.error('PDF generation error:', error);
+     return NextResponse.json(
+       { error: 'Failed to generate PDF', details: error instanceof Error ? error.message : 'Unknown error' },
+       { status: 500 }
+     );
+   }
+ }
+

+ import { getDeckContent, updateDeckContent, resetDeckContent, DeckContent } from '@/lib/deck-content';

+   try {
+     const content = getDeckContent();
+     return NextResponse.json(content);
+   } catch (error) {
+     console.error('Error fetching deck content:', error);
+     return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Failed to fetch content' }, { status: 500 });
+   }
+ }
+ 
+ export async function PUT(request: Request) {
+   try {
+     const body = await request.json() as Partial&lt;DeckContent&gt;;
+     const updatedContent = updateDeckContent(body);
+     return NextResponse.json(updatedContent);
+   } catch (error) {
+     console.error('Error updating deck content:', error);
+     return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Failed to update content' }, { status: 500 });
+   }
+ }
+ 
+ export async function DELETE() {
+   try {
+     const content = resetDeckContent();
+     return NextResponse.json(content);
+   } catch (error) {
+     console.error('Error resetting deck content:', error);
+     return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Failed to reset content' }, { status: 500 });
+   }
+ }

---

The pitch deck content is now editable and shared between both the web and PDF versions. Here's what I created:

**Architecture:**
1. **Shared Content Store** (`lib/deck-content.ts`) - Stores all deck text in a structured format, persisted to `data/deck-content.json`

2. **Admin Editor** (`/admin/deck`) - Full WYSIWYG-ish editor where you can:
   - Edit cover slide (title, tagline, subtagline, URL)
   - Edit each of the 14 content slides (title, subtitle, sections, bullet points, highlights, footnotes)
   - Edit the "Ask" section (amount and list of items)
   - Save changes that persist across server restarts
   - Reset to defaults if needed

3. **API Route** (`/api/deck-content`) - GET/PUT/DELETE endpoints for content management

**Usage:**
- Go to `/admin/deck` (after logging in) to edit the deck content
- Changes save to a JSON file and immediately reflect on both:
  - The homepage (`/`) 
  - The PDF pitch deck (`/deck`)
- Click "Refresh" on the deck page to regenerate the PDF after making edits
- The "Preview" button in the editor opens the deck page in a new tab

**File persistence:**
- Content is stored in `data/deck-content.json`
- Survives server restarts
- Can be version controlled if you want to track changes in git
